    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-05-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-05-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="395"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d395">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">863.51 Relief Credits/234</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Edge</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-05-23">May 23,
                            1930</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 170</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has received your despatch No.
                    517, dated May 2, 1930,<note n="16" xml:id="d395fn16">Not printed; see telegram
                        No. 126, May 2, 4 p.m., from the Ambassador in France, <ref target="#pg_399"
                            >p. 399</ref>.</note> transmitting the reply of the French Government to
                    the Embassy’s inquiry regarding the Austrian loan pursuant to the Department’s
                    cabled instruction No. 93 of April 15, 6 p.m., to the Embassy at London.</p>
                <p>The reply of the French Government is not directly responsive to the Department’s
                    inquiry on behalf of the Treasury Department. The Embassy is requested to
                    endeavor to obtain from the French Government a statement in substance that Sir
                    Frederick Leith-Ross’ letter of April 16, 1930, to the Austrian Minister at
                    London is approved by the French Government and was made pursuant to its
                    authority.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis White</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
